title: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving

heading_context: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
chunks.html_content: You must tell DVLA if your attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or your ADHD medication affects your ability to drive safely.
chunks.plain_content:
Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
You must tell DVLA if your attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or your ADHD medication affects your ability to drive safely.

heading_context: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
chunks.html_content: You can be fined up to £1,000 if you do not tell DVLA about a medical condition that affects your driving. You may be prosecuted if you’re involved in an accident as a result.
chunks.plain_content:
Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
You can be fined up to £1,000 if you do not tell DVLA about a medical condition that affects your driving. You may be prosecuted if you’re involved in an accident as a result.

heading_context: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
If you’re applying for your provisional (learners) driving licence
chunks.html_content:
You do not need to tell DVLA about your condition unless you think that it may affect your ability to drive safely.

Ask your doctor if you’re not sure if your condition will affect your driving.
chunks.plain_content:
Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
If you’re applying for your provisional (learners) driving licence
You do not need to tell DVLA about your condition unless you think that it may affect your ability to drive safely.
Ask your doctor if you’re not sure if your condition will affect your driving.

heading_context: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and driving
chunks.html_content:
If you already have a car or motorcycle licence you need to tell DVLA if:

  • there is a change to your condition that may make you an unsafe driver
  • you are prescribed medication that causes side effects that will affect your driving

Fill in form A1 and send it to DVLA. The address is on the form.

Fill in form A1V and send it to DVLA. The address is on the form.
